projects.description:
The primary focus of this project funded by Power to Change is the role and impact of community-based social enterprises in three European countries: the UK, the Netherlands and Sweden. Community-based social enterprises (CBSEs) are distinct from social enterprises by defining their purpose, benefits and management in relation to communities in defined areas. The three countries selected are similar in economic circumstances, in the impact of austerity on traditional welfare support programs, and in a desire to develop and enhance the contribution of social and community enterprise to fulfill unmet needs. It is our hypothesis, however, that there are also substantial differences based on historical, cultural and contextual factors. In all three countries there is strong evidence that CBSEs have developed rapidly through innovative approaches to co-production and changing citizen-government relationships. Despite a continuing debate about the meanings and definitions of the sector, this project seeks to explore the similarities and differences between these countries, particularly where CBSEs are making a significant contribution towards urban regeneration and reducing inequalities and deprivation. The main project objectives are to:

1.	Identify the national and local policy parameters in which CBSEs are located in order to identify how they have evolved and the legal, technical and political framework in which they operate in relation to broader societal and regeneration objectives;
2.	Review sources and levels of technical and financial support available from stakeholders and national bodies and to determine the extent to which these are critical to achieving sustainability and organizational objectives;
3.	Determine through case studies the methods and extent to which performance outputs and impact are monitored and evaluated;
4.	Generate findings and broader conclusions of direct relevance to local and national stakeholders, and the wider EU community.
